div.div: Adds FIDE player rating variables and collection information to the proposal document

Adds data collection and validation for chess games
Implements functionality to collect and validate chess game data, including user ratings, game outcomes, and opening classifications.
Ensures the dataset is cleaned and filtered for analysis, providing meaningful insights into player performance.
If no data is collected, generates simulated data for demonstration purposes.

Adds secondary analysis dimensions for player demographics
Introduces new categories for analyzing player demographics, including age groups, geographic regions, title categories, and activity levels.
This enhancement supports a more nuanced understanding of player behavior and characteristics, facilitating deeper insights in future analyses.
Adds cross-validation strategy section with details on temporal validation for model performance assessment
Adds time control predictions and insights on performance variance across different chess formats
Adds multi-group analysis methods including ANOVA, Kruskal-Wallis tests, post-hoc testing, and effect size calculations

Adds chess categorization by rating tier and opening type
Introduces new sections categorizing chess games based on player rating tiers and opening types.
This enhancement aids users in understanding the skill levels and strategies associated with different chess openings, improving the overall educational value of the document.

Adds enhanced data collection function with error handling
Implements a robust data collection function for retrieving user game data from the Lichess API.
Enhancements include: - Comprehensive error handling for API requests and data parsing. - Rate limiting to prevent overwhelming the API. - Improved data extraction for detailed game analysis.
This update ensures better reliability and user feedback during data collection processes.

Adds research questions to the proposal document
Introduces a set of research questions focusing on the statistical analysis of chess performance and player progression.
These questions aim to explore the impact of opening choices, playing frequency, and player ratings on game outcomes and efficiency.
Enhancing the document provides greater clarity on the research objectives.

Adds sample size and power analysis requirements
Introduces minimum sample size requirements for various analyses, enhancing the reliability of color analysis, time control comparisons, and rating tier evaluations.
Includes power calculations to ensure adequate effect size detection, statistical power, and confidence intervals for future studies.

Adds control variables and confounding factors for analysis
Introduces player-level, game-level, and environmental controls to enhance the understanding of factors influencing chess performance.
These additions aim to provide a more comprehensive framework for analyzing the impact of various elements on player outcomes.
Add expected group differences for color-based advantages in chess analysis

Adds game type classifications and statistical comparison methods
Introduces classifications for various chess game types, detailing characteristics from Bullet to Classical formats.
Enhances the statistical framework with methods for pairwise comparisons, including t-tests, chi-square tests, and rank-sum tests, to improve analysis capabilities.
Add setup chunk for knitr and integrate FIDE data processing steps
Refine data analysis structure by adding comparison groups and detailing primary grouping variables

Adds data cleaning steps for Lichess API integration
Introduces a section outlining the process for importing, standardizing, and cleaning data from the Lichess API.
Details include recoding categorical fields, deriving computed variables, and integrating FIDE data for enhanced analysis.
These changes improve data integrity and usability for subsequent analyses.
Add data analysis plan and naming conventions to proposal
Add launch configuration for R-Debugger in VSCode

Adds data information section for Lichess API and Database
Introduces an informative section detailing the Lichess Public API and Game Database.
This addition enhances understanding of the data sources used for the statistical analysis of chess performance and player progression, providing context for future analysis and research.
Update project proposal title, author, and output format
Created new branch secondary in Math-225-Fa2025/project-tmchuynh

Adds initial HTML structure for Lab 07 project
Creates a new HTML file that establishes the basic layout and styling for the Lab 07 project, focusing on presenting data related to smokers in Whickham.
Includes a script to ensure compatibility with different Pandoc versions and defines comprehensive CSS styles for various elements to enhance readability and presentation.
No related issues or tickets are referenced.

Adds bar plot visualization for health outcomes by age and smoking
Improves data presentation by adding a bar plot that visualizes health outcomes based on smoking status and age category.
This change enhances the analysis by providing a clear visual representation, making it easier to interpret the relationship between smoking and health outcomes across different age groups.

Adds age categorization to Whickham dataset
Implements a new age categorization feature in the Whickham dataset by creating an `age_cat` variable.
This enhancement allows for better analysis of health outcomes by age group in subsequent visualizations and narratives.
Facilitates improved understanding of smoking status relationships across different age categories.

Adds visualization of health outcomes by smoking status
Implements a bar chart to depict the proportion of health outcomes based on smoking status.
This change enhances the data presentation, making it easier to analyze the relationship between smoking and health outcomes visually.

Adds expected relationship between smoking and health outcomes
Clarifies the anticipated negative health impacts of smoking, highlighting the established connection between smoking and increased mortality rates due to various diseases.
Enhances understanding of smoking's effects in the context of the analysis.

Adds visualizations for age, smoking status, and outcome
Introduces ggplot visualizations to enhance data analysis.
Includes histograms for age distribution and bar charts for smoking status and health outcome, facilitating better understanding of relationships in the dataset.

Adds variable descriptions for dataset analysis
Includes detailed descriptions of the three variables in the dataset:
- Age: Continuous variable (numeric) - Smoker: Categorical variable (factor with levels "yes" and "no") - Outcome: Categorical variable (factor with levels "alive" and "dead")
This enhances clarity for understanding the dataset structure and aids in analysis.

Adds observation details to dataset description
Clarifies that the dataset contains 5000 observations, with each observation representing an individual participant along with their age, smoking status at baseline, and health outcome after 20 years.

Adds reasoning for observational study classification
Includes an explanation for classifying the dataset as an observational study, noting the lack of variable manipulation by researchers.
This enhances the clarity of the analysis regarding the study's design and methodology.

Updates author name and output formats in R Markdown
Changes the author name to Tina Huynh and updates the output formats for the document.
Introduces a PDF output option with table of contents and numbered sections, while maintaining the existing Tufte HTML format.
These updates enhance the document's usability and presentation.

Update college majors PDF with revised content
Replaces the existing college majors PDF with an updated version containing revised information.
This change addresses inaccuracies in the previous document and enhances clarity for users referencing major options.
Update XeTeX version timestamp and memory usage in log file
Update author name to Tina Huynh and enhance analysis on median income distributions and unemployment rates in college majors
Renames histogram plot chunk and adjusts height for better visualization

Adds analysis of unemployment rates by major category
Introduces a new analysis to examine how unemployment varies across different major categories in the dataset.
The changes include a summarization of median and average unemployment rates, along with the total number of graduates per major category, to provide insights into the relationship between field size and unemployment rates.

Adds scatterplot of median income vs. proportion of women
Introduces a scatterplot visualization to analyze the relationship between median income and the proportion of women in various college majors, categorized by major type (STEM vs Non-STEM).
Enhances data exploration capabilities and allows for better understanding of gender composition's impact on income.

Adds filtering for STEM majors with low median salaries
Implements a filter to identify STEM majors with median salaries below $36,000.
This change enhances the analysis of college majors by focusing on those that may need further attention regarding earning potential.
The results will display the major name along with median, 25th percentile, and 75th percentile earnings, sorted by median earning in descending order.

Improves major category count by sorting results
Adds sorting to the count of major categories for better readability and analysis of the data.
Ensures that the output is organized in ascending order based on the count, enhancing data presentation.

Improves median income analysis for college majors
Refines the summarization of median incomes by major category to accurately identify the typical median.
Updates the summarization process to calculate and arrange the median in descending order, facilitating the identification of the highest median income category.
Additionally, prepares the code for future enhancements related to counting observations in each category.

Adds histogram plot for median income by major category
Implements a histogram visualization of median income, faceted by major category, to better analyze the distribution of incomes among different college majors.
This addition enhances the understanding of income distribution patterns, aiding in the identification of the most typical median income across categories.

Clarifies statistical description of income distributions
Updates the explanation of statistical summary measures for median incomes, emphasizing the use of median and interquartile range due to right-skewness in the data.
Replaces previous points with a more detailed analysis of histogram shapes and their implications for the choice of summary statistics, ensuring better understanding for future reference.

Updates binwidth recommendations for histogram analysis
Revises the binwidth options for the histogram of median incomes to improve clarity and detail in data visualization.
Explains the rationale for choosing a binwidth of $5000, highlighting its ability to balance detail and overall distribution visibility, while reducing clutter from excessive bins.
Includes example code for implementing the new binwidth in the histogram.

Adds explanation for choosing median over mean income
Clarifies the rationale for selecting the median as a measure of typical income, highlighting its robustness against outliers in income distributions.
Enhances understanding of income representation in the context of college majors.

Updates author name and adds top majors by women proportion
Changes the author name to Tina Huynh.
Introduces a code block that arranges data to display the top 3 college majors by the proportion of women, enhancing data presentation and analysis.
